Regional Influences towards COVID Vaccinations¶

Author: Mateos O'Connor

Introduction¶

Although faced with the COVID-19 pandemic and its variants, the necessity to receive vaccinations have become increasingly important. That being said, there are those who believe that what the CDC is giving out could be harmful for them and their loved ones. In addition, there is already a small population that is against vaccinations entirely. For any disease, the biggest risk factor is others that aren't immunized. By analyzing the trend for 2021, we should be able to not just observe the different regions of the United States that present an issue during this pandemic, but we can notice the future trend for national cases if vaccinations are still being resisted.

In this project, I will first observe the vaccination trends of each region, and analyze the correlation between the number of cases and these different regions.

dates_for_data = ['1/12/2021', '2/12/2021', '3/12/2021', '4/12/2021', '5/12/2021', '6/12/2021',
                  '7/12/2021', '8/12/2021', '9/12/2021', '10/12/2021', '11/12/2021', '12/12/2021']

df = data.loc[data['submission_date'] == '1/12/2021']

#filter so that each state has only one row for each month
for y in dates_for_data[1:]:
    df2 = data.loc[data['submission_date'] == y]
    df = df.append(df2, ignore_index=True)

#change date so the date matches with the second dataset
for x in dates_for_data:
    temp = pd.to_datetime(x, format="%m/%d/%Y")
    temp = temp.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
    df = df.replace(to_replace = x, value = temp)

#filter out all locations besides US states (like Puerto Rico)
all_loc = data.state
all_loc = all_loc.unique()
all_loc
for x in all_loc:
    if abbrev_to_us_state.get(x) is None:
        df = df.drop(df.loc[df['state']==x].index)
    else:
        continue
df = df.reset_index()
df = df.drop(columns='index')

Above, I have to reformat the date and state abbreviations, so that they match another table I will be joining together. This also makes great use of the dictionary, because it had values other than the 50 states, like Puerto Rico and Cuba. If that key appears, it is taken out of the table so that they are not counted in our Regional comparison.

Visualization¶

Now that we have our table, we can now show the current trend throughout the year for the entire nation. I have made a new array to store each month of the year, for the visual graphs. I did not want to present each x-value as a long date, when it is only one instance-per-month

allcases = []
cases_over_time = []
death_over_time = []
total_vax_over_time = []
months = ['Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
terps = df.groupby(['submission_date'])

for x in terps:
    allcases.append(np.nansum(x[1].tot_cases))
    cases_over_time.append(np.nansum(x[1].tot_cases)/1000000)
    death_over_time.append(np.nansum(x[1].tot_death)/1000000)
    total_vax_over_time.append(np.nansum(x[1].people_vaccinated)/1000000)

I chose to filter the results, and make the data representative in the millions, to make it easier to view.

Identifying a Relationship to Region¶

However, I have predicted that overall vaccinations will have been affected by the different regions throughout the states. While living in Alabama, I found that there was little caution and care towards the pandemic. I found rarely anyone with masks on, and local talk of vaccine fear. However, in places such as the Northeastern region, lockdown steps had been put in place, and masks became mandatory.

Because of this assumption, I believe there will be at least one region that belongs above the regression line, and one that falls, thus dragging down the slope of the regression.

The linear regression that I will be performing will be used to analyze the future trends for COVID-19 cases, given the variables of the month, vaccinated number, and death count. This will allow us to see past what we have, in order to speculate on further action about the problem of vaccination.

This regression using the Ordinary-Least Squares model actually shows a lot. I knew that it was correlated between the number of cases and deaths(since you need to have COVID in the first place), but I thought that the coefficient between the total cases and the number of vaccinated individuals would be negative. This will have to be further investigated, but a quick analysis of this could be that people become more lenient when they get vaccinated, and put themselves at risk more often as a result.

Extra Analysis¶

One of the biggest issue with the Vaccination rate is the fact that eligibilty for vaccination initially centered around age, in descending order. That meant those older would get their vaccinations before children. This poses a potential cause, since children are typically in a more crowded environment than adults. Regardless of quarantine, we should look at the larger causes of the rise in cases. Since children were able to be vaccinated after May 2021, we can look before and after. Therefore, the first five months could infer a relationship with the trend.

Conclusion¶

This model has clearly shown that while there are different elements that might impact the cases of COVID-19, doubt and lack of immunization is what will continue this linear growth of infection. Most importantly from this data, we have found that those who are vaccinated are also at risk of COVID-19. a vaccine does not mean you are completely immune, especially since this piece of data only counted if they had the first dose. Although there are regions that are troublesome, the growth will not stop until there is change within society to appeal to those who are doubtful of the current state of vaccinations.

Hopefully this project has not only served to inform you of the importance of immunization, but allowed you to understand the Data Science Cycle, and the potential it displays for the future.
